          "body": "The chapter opens with a scene of apparent piety: elders of Israel in Babylon come and sit before the prophet (14:1). In every other context this would be a scene of covenant fidelity — leaders seeking God's word through His appointed spokesman. But God interrupts before Ezekiel can speak a word. He tells the prophet what He already knows about the men sitting before him: they have 'set up their idols in their hearts' and placed 'the stumbling block of their iniquity right before their faces' (14:3). The Hebrew gillul — Ezekiel's contempt-word for idols, rooted in a term for dung — is not the word for the Babylonian statues they may have adopted in exile. It is what God sees when He looks at the inner sanctuary of their hearts. The diagnostic is devastating: the elders have come to the right place (the prophet), at the right time (a moment of national crisis), with the right form (sitting, inquiring) — and the entire exercise is corrupted at the root because the heart belongs elsewhere. This interior idol-temple is Ezekiel's deepest pastoral diagnosis, and it is still the first question God asks of every inquirer."
