          "body": "God's response to the idol-harboring inquirer is not silence — it is something more terrifying. He announces in 14:4-5 that He will 'be brought to give him an answer in the matter in view of the multitude of his idols.' This is not divine guidance; it is divine judicial exposure. God answers the divided heart by confronting it with what it has actually chosen. The stated purpose clarifies the mechanism: 'in order to lay hold of the hearts of the house of Israel who are estranged from Me through all their idols' (14:5). The answer God gives to the idol-harboring inquirer is calculated to break through the self-deception that allows a man to think he can have God's word and his idols simultaneously. This pattern has canonical precedent in 1 Kings 22:20-23, where God sends a lying spirit into the mouths of Ahab's prophets — a judicial hardening that exposes Ahab's determination to hear only what he wants to hear. Ezekiel's elders are in the same position: they will receive an answer commensurate with their idols rather than with their professed inquiry."
