          "body": "Having named the diagnosis, God issues a command rather than closing the door permanently: 'Repent and turn away from your idols and turn your faces away from all your abominations' (14:6). The verb 'turn' (shuv) is the OT's primary word for repentance — a full directional change. The command comes before the judicial sentence of 14:7-8, which means it is genuinely possible: God is not pronouncing doom before offering the alternative. But for those who refuse to turn — who still come to the prophet with idols enthroned and stumbling blocks planted — the sentence is total. God will 'set My face against that man,' make him 'a sign and a proverb,' and 'cut him off from among My people' (14:8). The phrase 'set My face against' is the precise antithesis of the Aaronic blessing ('the Lord make His face shine upon you,' Numbers 6:25). To have God's face set against you is to lose the one thing the covenant promises. And the recognition formula closes the sentence: 'So you will know that I am the Lord' (14:8) — even covenant judgment is a revelation of divine identity."
