        "number": 4,
        "title": "Jerusalem named — 'how much more' and the four severe judgments",
        "range": "14:21",
        "excerpt": "How much more when I send My four severe judgments against Jerusalem: sword, famine, wild beasts and plague to cut off man and beast from it!",
        "body": "Verse 21 is the hinge on which the entire second oracle turns. The particle 'how much more' (ki aph ki) is the classic Hebrew a fortiori marker, signaling that the hypothetical principle of 14:13-20 is now being applied with intensified force to a real and named situation. The four judgments — sword, famine, wild beasts, plague — are not new; they have been announced and dramatized across chapters 4-13 of Ezekiel. What is new in 14:21 is the explicit naming of Jerusalem as the country to which the universal principle applies, and the explicit enumeration of all four at once.\n\nThe fourfold judgment list echoes Leviticus 26:21-26 and Deuteronomy 32:23-25, where God's covenant curses are catalogued as the consequences of persistent rebellion. Ezekiel's four here are the concentrated fulfillment of what the covenant warned across centuries. By naming all four simultaneously in 14:21, God is saying that Jerusalem's judgment will not be partial — it will be the full covenant-curse package, all four agents deployed together. Daniel Block (New International Commentary on Ezekiel) notes that this fourfold combination appears in several ANE texts as the full complement of divine judgment agents, suggesting that Ezekiel's audience would have recognized the total-war imagery immediately.\n\nThe logic of 14:21 in relation to the second oracle (14:12-20) is devastating for the exiles' hope. If even in a single-agent judgment (famine alone, or wild beasts alone, or sword alone, or plague alone) a Noah, Daniel, or Job could not extend their righteousness to save others — how much more impossible is deliverance when all four agents are deployed at once against a city whose covenant treachery has been accumulating for generations? The 'how much more' is not merely rhetorical emphasis; it is theological conclusion: Jerusalem's judgment is irreversible, comprehensive, and just.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shephet* (judgments, v.21) — divine acts of executing sentence, from the root to judge. *Ra* (severe/dire) — here an intensifier meaning evil in the sense of destructive, not morally evil in the sense of sinful. The four agents — *cherev* (sword), *raav* (famine), *chay ra* (wild beasts), *dever* (plague) — are Ezekiel's standard quartet, appearing also in Revelation 6:8 as the four horsemen, confirming that this canonical motif extends into the New Testament's eschatological vision."
